I. INTRODUCTION\'a0\
Proof of work is work.\'a0 Appealing to the economic theory put forth by the classical political economists Adam Smith, David Ricardo, and updated at the beginning of the industrial age by Karl Marx, all new value comes from human labour. Any monetary unit used for the exchange of value must thus represent a portion of socially necessary labour time, as can be observed in the proportional relationship between the cost of labour and the price of the products of that labour in that monetary unit.\'a0 The relation between a unit of money and the amount of labour it represents must be a fixed 
\f2\i ratio
\f1\i0 .\'a0\
\
In the age of computation, the labour principle of value creation has not been superseded. The precision hardware, infrastructure, power generation are all available thanks to human labour either contemporary or recorded in and performed by automated hardware.\'a0\
\
In a 
\f2\i rational
\f1\i0  distributed cryptocurrency system verified by Proof of Work cryptographic hashing, the issuance of the unit of cryptocurrency should correspond directly to the amount of cryptographic \'93work\'94 or hashes needed to verify each block of transactions added to the ledger.\'a0 The qualifier \'93rational\'94 in this sense merely indicates that there is a stable work:coin ratio.\'a0 Most cryptocurrency systems such as Bitcoin are not rational, and therefore according to the LToV, their true value is zero (reference: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://blog.p2pfoundation.net/face-value-bitcoin-proof-work-labour-theory-value/2018/02/01"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 https://blog.p2pfoundation.net/face-value-bitcoin-proof-work-labour-theory-value/2018/02/01}} )\'a0\'a0 Such crypto currency instruments which decouple the reward (or "subsidy" as in Bitcoin) from the work required to maintain the reliability of the system are prey to various speculative manipulations such as arbitrage, with the result that these latter financial instruments will never be money, there use will always be predicated on exchanges through other institutional, financial devices such as fiat currency. Cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin will remain volatile asset classes and never become money, and thus can never live up to the expectation that they can provide an alternative basis for economies of scale outside the current banking system. Haket, a 
\f2\i rational
\f1\i0  crytocurrency, can be a distributed money.\'a0\
